    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin confusion. Let's clear up the process without the mythical creatures. When you decide to buy a house, the money involved in the transaction is typically held in an escrow account. Here's how it works:\n\n1. You agree to buy the house and the seller agrees to sell it.\n2. You provide a deposit to the escrow agent, which is usually a title company or an attorney.\n3. The escrow agent holds your deposit in a secure account until the closing.\n4. The seller receives the deposit and agrees to the terms of the sale.\n5. Once all the conditions of the sale are met, the escrow agent releases the funds to the seller and the title of the house to you.\n\nThis process ensures that the seller doesn't receive the money until you've signed the necessary paperwork and the house is officially yours, and it ensures that you don't lose your deposit if something goes wrong with the sale. It's a way to protect both parties involved in the transaction.",
